 weapon for both USA and Yugoslavia in the Cold War battle for hearts and minds. Radina Vučetić explores how the Party used American culture in order to promote its own values and what life in this socialist and capitalist hybrid system looked like for ordinary people who lived in a country with communist ideology in a capitalist wrapping. Her book offers a careful reevaluation of the limits of appropriating the American dream and questions both an uncritical celebration of Yugoslavia’s openness and an exaggerated depiction of its authoritarianism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aCommunism and culturezYugoslavia. 0aNineteen sixties. 0aPopular culture and globalizationy20th century. 0aPopular culturezUnited States. 0aPopular culturezYugoslavia. 0aSocialism and culturezYugoslavia. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Eastern.2bisacsh  aCommunism, Cultural studies, Yugoslavia, Socialism, United States, Customs and traditions.1 aCox, John K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2018z978311078052940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789633862018423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789633862018/original  a978-3-11-078052-9  Central European University Press eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK